description.text:
Uppdate 24-11-2015
( I have uppdated the bearing blocks. https://youtu.be/QRKUzB4lhs4 The top rail is not nesseseary, the machine works perfectly, but beacause of the orifginal Creatr design the motor shafts keep failing due to metal fatigue. The new blocks have reinforsments where needed and its made so you can remove the 2 nutts on the y axis bearing and move the motor sprocket inn in the axsle so the motor shaft wont fail. this new design has run for over 800 hours without insident. The bearing holes are also enlarged adn are now oversized, you get better bearing function this way just epoxy the slide bearings in place.) I knew i would get totally fed up with my Creatr's shortcomings soner or later so i have made a bunch of parts with the goal in mind to fix it permanently.
The power chain is in the way, the exstruder carriage is wobbly and very veak.
Here is a video illustrating the problem. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s5jMjxTiCow
It actually warps the exstruder carriage in spite of me having stiffened it up with a 12 mm top rail. So i am doing some major changes.
Im fixing the x axis, the y axis the exstruders and the cable chain.
It works perfectly, the accurasy is superb and since i have new igus slide bearings on my X axis its tigt as hell 0 drift and no vibrations at all.
http://youtu.be/2J2w01iNqAI
Now my printer makes perfect parts every time, and i can use the entire build volume.
Each of the improvements are available in stand alone versions.
This is the combination version with slightly different parts. Do not try to do this unless you have the patience and know what you are doing
PS: you dont actually need the top rail anymore, its stiff as hell and works wonderfull without it.
Instruktions will be posted on as i develope the solution http://www.kundesalg.no.

description.text: The bottom of the ocean and the Hawaiian Archipelago are modeled. Vertical exaggeration is 25x. 3.6 million facets in the .stl file. From the ETOPO2 database. this is one tile of 32 tiles of Earth elevations. The Smith & Sandwell  report explains how the satellites measured the seafloor depths by observing the changes in the height of the water due to gravity.

Major Sources of Data:
The seafloor data between latitudes 64° North and 72° South are from the work of Smith and Sandwell (1997). These data were derived from satellite altimetry observations combined with carefully, quality-assured shipboard echo-sounding measurements, by Dr. Walter H.F. Smith, of the NOAA Laboratory for Satellite Altimetry and Dr. David T. Sandwell, of the Institute of Geophysics and Planetary Physics at the University of California, San Diego. Data version 8.2 is used here.
For reference on generation of these data, consult:

Seafloor data southward of 72° South are from the US Naval Oceanographic Office's (NAVOCEANO) Digital Bathymetric Data Base Variable Resolution (DBDBV), version 4.1, gridded at 5 minute spacing; some data in this region are from the older DBDB5 (these data were also used in ETOPO5). Drop the nuts into the extrusion (yes you can do it from the top no need to open up the side). screw the parts to the Misumi and slide them together. Screw holes are M5. If you put the nut in the correct direction then you just need to slide the mount and the hole should be over the nut.
The Extruder screw traps are M4.
The fillament Nut Trap is M6.
The top joining nut trap is M5 The Extruder Mount in the New LongHoles version should fit most extruders or if your fillament hole is not in the standard position. description.text:
This adaptor fits e3d hotend to a 3Drag/K8200 printer,
without integrated fan duct (my hotend had a nice molded one
included).
Very simple but rigid and work well.
BOM:
+1 pcs. adaptor.
+4 pcs. M3 nuts.
+4pcs M3x18mm (or longer) bolts. All 4 are included on your
standard hotend and can be reused.

-Print upside down compared to when mounted on printer. (I tried borh ways and the 45 deg slopes get much better finish when turned up)
I used ABS 0.2mm layers, 0.3mm extrusion width, 0.5mm nozzle.
I think PLA will do just as well. Warmth is not an issue, my upper slice of heat sink is room tempered when the nozzle is 250 deg Celsius.
1) Print the adaptor.
2) Drill all 6 holes to 3mm, just to be sure...
3) Put the 2 halves together around the heat sink, with the 2 horizontal bolts, as shown pictures. Notice that the bolts are oriented in opposite directions. This is because the 2 halves are identical. (No need to have different spare parts). DO NOT turn too hard (I know it is tempting).
4) Mount it all at the 2 bolts sticking out vertically where you removed your previous hotend. This can be hard, but use a screwdriver or similar to put pressure from top so that the 2 bolts penetrate the holes.
5) Mount the 2 nuts.
6) Enjoy!

title: Braun HL1 - Personal Desktop Fan - vintage

description.text:
This is a fairly accurate model of the iconic Braun HL1.

I built only the fan shroud originally to restore the two fans I have as they are the parts that seem to be showing their age the most--and seem to be the trickiest to get clean and clear! They are integral to the assembly to the item, so I created the part accurately enough to reproduce the actual part in transparent resin 3D print but feel it may actually look quite interesting in an opaque color--as a sort of resto-mod.

In any event, I got carried away with the process and built the entire desktop fan.

The shroud itself is now available for purchase at Shapeways.com.

This is an extendable structure that should be helpful to quickly try some gearchains.
Its somewhat similar to an optical laboratory table - just less big heavy stiff and level. It also has striking similarity to those flat lego pieces (not intended).

Sandwitch some (e.g. three or more) layers of gears between two layers of these structures. Adjust the distance between the layers to leave sufficient clearing with some distributed spacertubes and screws (either printed or vitamin)

The axles are supposed to be printed flat cut to a thickness of 2*radius/sqrt(2) this makes sure overhangs are <= 45° and this way one can make gears that either couple to the axle or not.
Options to keep the axles from sliding out are
  • widen the axle at one point
  • slim the axle at one point and use cliprings
  • use plates with closed caps

description.text:
Hello!
This is a relatively big (140x110x55 mm) 3-D printed peristaltic pump. It can be powerd by your cordless drill.
There are five parts to print and a few other materials needed
(please see the instructions)
Alterations and suggestions to improve it are very welcome, have fun!
Andrew

As mentioned in the description, you will need these materials (apart from the five prints):

5x 608 bearings
3x M8 bolts (20mm long)
1x M8 bolt (80mm long)
4x M5 bolts (50 mm long)
2x M5 bolts (25mm long)
6x M5 nuts
10x M5 washers
hose: something around 6 mm in outer diameter
The assembly of the pump is showed in the pictures, not depicted in the images are the four M5 bolts that hold everything together.
Note: The pump case may need a little bit of support material, since there are four bigger holes at the bottom. The rest is planned to print without support material.
Detailed information concerning the hose: There is about 2 mm space between the bearings of the rotor and the case wall.

comments.text: how much l/minute does is pump, and at how many psi / bar?

comments.text:
Hi! That's a good question, didn't measure the flow rate yet, because I am planning on an DC motor casing with some kind of coupling and/or gearbox for this pump. After that, measuring will be easier.
For the pressure difference I can't say much about, but because of the still existing gap between the roller bearings and the squeezed tube, there is mentionable reflow, therefore there not much pressure build-up. I used it only in an atmospheric setup so far :)
Nevertheless, this pump is capable of moving liquid quite nicely, but it was not made to perform better than off-the-shelf-pumps.
kind regards,
Andrew

description.text: I do apologize for the lack of updates on this, however a serious of unfortunate events had crippled my progress. During a modification for a better heated platform, I fried 3 transistors, one atmega, one power supply and broke two extruder mounts while I am at. I almost have all parts to get back and going, just need to find some time.
This is a tentative Thingiverse model until I finalize all parts and populate the gallery with video and more pictures.

Another auto bed level idea that can be adapted to fit your printer,
although I originally did it for my Solidoodle 3.

I got tired of performing man leveling of the bed after each print,
and I didn't have any servos lying around, so I wanted to make use
of an opto-switch that I had slavaged off on older printer that I used to have.

• Uses an opto-switch (or opto-endstop)
  • Spring loaded for automatic operation
  • Doesn't use any servos or any extra pins/soldering.
  • Relatively simple to print and use.
  • If by accident, the extruder moves to the bed while the nail is extended, it won't break as it has some give to it, but ultimately it'll break as shown in the picture without causing any damage to the bed or anything else.

    Test run

    The cylinder you see in the pictures was actually printed on the un-level bed shown in the pictures as well. I think it performed very well, thanks to Marlin auto-bed-leveling feature.

http://youtu.be/xx5szf5JKZQ
http://youtu.be/LzPoxXpYCF8

I'll post more details later, but for now you'll need:
1x Spring of acceptable size and force
1x Finished Nail 2" long
1x 8mm Magnet
1x Modified Lawsy's MK5 extruder mount (see files)
2x Screws (will get back on the size/type)
